    "narrative": "Today\u2019s optimal lineup for Ghost Ride the WHIP is anchored by **Mickey Moniak**, whose score of 75.75 makes him our most potent asset. He benefits from a favorable matchup against Strider, where a combination of a hitter-friendly park and a +14% platoon boost elevates him to the top of our priority list. Close behind, **Seiya Suzuki** (68.08) and **Austin Riley** (67.79) are must-starts. **Seiya Suzuki** is specifically targeted for his ability to capitalize on the slower delivery of Kelly, which creates a prime opportunity to exploit SB potential\u2014a critical factor given our league's scarcity mandate. **Vinnie Pasquantino** also cracks the top tier (67.69) by leveraging a strong platoon advantage against Castillo, despite the park penalty, proving that the algorithm heavily favors the right-handed bat against this specific starter.\n\nOur most difficult bench decision involved **Cole Young**, who flirted with the lineup at 44.59 but ultimately yielded to the superior projected efficiency of the active starters. While **Cole Young** possesses the speed metrics we covet, the combination of a difficult platoon split and the depth of our infield options pushed him to the sidelines. Elsewhere, we are closely monitoring the risks associated with **Corbin Carroll** (58.48); while his speed is vital, he faces an \"Elite Hold\" pitcher in Boyd, which tempers his overall efficiency score significantly. Similarly, **Jose Caballero** (55.35) remains in the lineup due to his high SB ceiling, though his raw projection is muted by a poor platoon matchup against Gibson.\n\nInvestors should note that we are managing an increasingly depleted bench with **Giancarlo Stanton** and **Max Muncy** sidelined on the IL, alongside **Trevor Story**, who is not currently in the lineup. With **Dalton Rushing** (53.25) and **James Wood** (53.56) providing necessary stability, our focus remains on protecting our game caps while ensuring our speed-first strategy remains 